WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.900 --> 00:00:09.580
MALE SPEAKER: I'm incredibly
excited to be on stage here

00:00:09.580 --> 00:00:19.410
introducing Andy Weir, the
author of "The Martian."

00:00:19.410 --> 00:00:21.300
I read the book last
year, and it was

00:00:21.300 --> 00:00:23.850
my favorite book of all 2014.

00:00:23.850 --> 00:00:27.050
And I've lost track of how
many engineer friends I have,

00:00:27.050 --> 00:00:29.960
that I respect, who also say
it was their favorite book

00:00:29.960 --> 00:00:32.244
of last year.

00:00:32.244 --> 00:00:33.160
Andy is the son of a--

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:35.201
ANDY WEIR: What about the
ones you don't respect?

00:00:35.201 --> 00:00:38.820
SPEAKER: They-- they think
it was not very good.

00:00:38.820 --> 00:00:40.612
Andy is the son of a
particle physicists

00:00:40.612 --> 00:00:42.320
and has a background
in computer science.

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:44.750
He began writing 'The
Martian' in 2009,

00:00:44.750 --> 00:00:46.850
researching related
material to try

00:00:46.850 --> 00:00:49.150
to make the book as
realistic as possible

00:00:49.150 --> 00:00:51.460
and based on real technology.

00:00:51.460 --> 00:00:54.290
Andy's book is an
extraordinary adventure

00:00:54.290 --> 00:00:58.870
about human ingenuity and humor
in the face of great odds.

00:00:58.870 --> 00:01:01.940
Although, it falls easily into
the science fiction genre,

00:01:01.940 --> 00:01:03.880
it's a book for every one.

00:01:03.880 --> 00:01:05.730
It has remained on
Amazon's best seller

00:01:05.730 --> 00:01:08.080
list since its
publication last year.

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:10.790
And it was the winner
of the 2015 Audie Award

00:01:10.790 --> 00:01:12.710
for best science fiction.

00:01:12.710 --> 00:01:14.850
A film version of
the book is actually

00:01:14.850 --> 00:01:17.790
coming out in October,
directed by Ridley Scott

00:01:17.790 --> 00:01:20.860
and starring Matt Damon
and Jessica Chastain.

00:01:20.860 --> 00:01:22.860
Please join me in
giving a Google warm

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:24.630
welcome. to Andy Weir.

00:01:24.630 --> 00:01:27.040
ANDY WEIR: Thank you.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:27.540
Hello.

00:01:31.420 --> 00:01:34.460
Hi everybody.

00:01:34.460 --> 00:01:36.020
Oh cool, the wander around mike.

00:01:36.020 --> 00:01:37.450
Good.

00:01:37.450 --> 00:01:39.100
So, I'll just give--
I'll preface this

00:01:39.100 --> 00:01:41.590
by saying I threw out
my back this morning.

00:01:41.590 --> 00:01:44.560
So, I may have to sit
down during my talk, which

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:47.270
is why they've set
up this chair for me.

00:01:47.270 --> 00:01:48.885
That's what I get
for turning 40.

00:01:52.600 --> 00:01:55.230
So, I'm going to tell you a
little bit about the story

00:01:55.230 --> 00:01:56.910
behind the story,
and then I'll get

00:01:56.910 --> 00:01:58.825
into the things you
actually care about,

00:01:58.825 --> 00:02:00.020
the details of the movie.

00:02:02.580 --> 00:02:04.040
So, I always wanted
to be a writer.

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:05.760
All my life I loved writing.

00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:07.270
I loved science fiction.

00:02:07.270 --> 00:02:10.630
I grew up with reading
my dad's endless supply

00:02:10.630 --> 00:02:13.400
of classic sci-fi,
which is interesting

00:02:13.400 --> 00:02:16.650
because he'd grown up
just collecting, kind of,

00:02:16.650 --> 00:02:18.600
pulpy sci-fi books.

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:21.215
And, so I ended up reading,
kind of, one generation off.

00:02:21.215 --> 00:02:23.700
I Don't think dad ever
thrown away a book.

00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:25.780
And he has- he had
a bookshelf that

00:02:25.780 --> 00:02:28.780
was about six feet high,
three feet wide, one foot deep

00:02:28.780 --> 00:02:31.620
just jam packed
full of sci-fi books

00:02:31.620 --> 00:02:33.760
from the '50s '60s and '70s.

00:02:33.760 --> 00:02:35.160
So that's what I
grew up reading.

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:38.049
And so my idols are Heinlein,
and Clarke, and Asimov.

00:02:38.049 --> 00:02:39.590
And a lot of those
books don't really

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:41.910
stand up today
especially when you

00:02:41.910 --> 00:02:45.150
talk about the role
of women in society.

00:02:45.150 --> 00:02:47.300
But if you grade
them on a curve,

00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:50.580
they're still really good.

00:02:50.580 --> 00:02:54.250
Anyway when the time came for
me to choose a college major,

00:02:54.250 --> 00:02:56.540
I kind of-- there were
two things I really liked.

00:02:56.540 --> 00:02:59.150
I liked writing and I
liked computer programming.

00:02:59.150 --> 00:03:01.920
And I wanted to be
a writer, but I also

00:03:01.920 --> 00:03:03.670
want to eat regular meals.

00:03:03.670 --> 00:03:07.110
And I wanted to live somewhere
other than a box in an alley,

00:03:07.110 --> 00:03:09.020
so I decided I'll be
a computer programmer.

00:03:09.020 --> 00:03:11.120
So I went into
computer programming.

00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:13.770
And I did that for
about 25 years.

00:03:13.770 --> 00:03:15.690
Or actually I started
when I was 15,

00:03:15.690 --> 00:03:18.160
because I ended up working
for a national lab in town.

00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:20.370
I grew up in
Livermore, California.

00:03:20.370 --> 00:03:20.870
Woo.

00:03:20.870 --> 00:03:24.040
There's a whoo.

00:03:24.040 --> 00:03:26.490
Thank you one person.

00:03:26.490 --> 00:03:29.970
And, so, I end up working there
as a test tube cleaner lab

00:03:29.970 --> 00:03:30.690
assistant guy.

00:03:30.690 --> 00:03:33.150
And they said, well, we don't
need you to clean test tubes,

00:03:33.150 --> 00:03:35.110
but we need someone to figure
out how to present this data.

00:03:35.110 --> 00:03:36.090
There's a computer.

00:03:36.090 --> 00:03:37.500
Here's a book on programming.

00:03:37.500 --> 00:03:39.850
Come back when you
figured it out.

00:03:39.850 --> 00:03:44.650
That began a 25 year career
in computer programming.

00:03:44.650 --> 00:03:46.220
Anyway, I went to college.

00:03:46.220 --> 00:03:48.550
And I actually dropped out
because I ran out of money,

00:03:48.550 --> 00:03:51.420
because that's kind of the
norm for my generation.

00:03:51.420 --> 00:03:55.860
And I ended up going into the
computer programming field.

00:03:55.860 --> 00:03:57.630
I worked for a couple places.

00:03:57.630 --> 00:04:00.320
I was actually one of the
programmers on Warcraft II,

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:01.900
when I worked for Blizzard.

00:04:01.900 --> 00:04:05.020
So, yes, you can thank
me for some of those lost

00:04:05.020 --> 00:04:07.070
productive hours of your youth.

00:04:07.070 --> 00:04:10.060
And then-- and then later
on I worked for AOL.

00:04:10.060 --> 00:04:12.020
And I worked for
AOL until 1999, when

00:04:12.020 --> 00:04:14.940
I got laid off along with
800 of my closest friends

00:04:14.940 --> 00:04:16.810
because they merged
with Netscape.

00:04:16.810 --> 00:04:19.240
Yes, that's how
long ago that was.

00:04:19.240 --> 00:04:21.440
Now at the time at a
bunch of stock options.

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:26.010
And, so, I was forced to
sell these stock options.

00:04:26.010 --> 00:04:28.770
I had 60 days to sell
them or lose them.

00:04:28.770 --> 00:04:33.530
So I sold at what turned out
to be AOL's peak price ever.

00:04:33.530 --> 00:04:36.400
So I assure you I would not have
made any sort of wise market

00:04:36.400 --> 00:04:38.010
decisions if left
to my own devices,

00:04:38.010 --> 00:04:39.949
but I was forced to do this.

00:04:39.949 --> 00:04:41.490
And I ended up with
a bunch of money.

00:04:41.490 --> 00:04:44.190
And I'm like, hey, I've got a
bunch of money, now is my shot.

00:04:44.190 --> 00:04:47.420
I can live for a few years
without having a job, which

00:04:47.420 --> 00:04:49.130
is good because it was 1999.

00:04:49.130 --> 00:04:53.570
All engineers lived a few
years without having a job.

00:04:53.570 --> 00:04:56.440
And I'm going to take my
shot at writing, here we go.

00:04:56.440 --> 00:04:58.020
I'm going to write a book.

00:04:58.020 --> 00:05:00.770
So I took three years
off, and I wrote a book.

00:05:00.770 --> 00:05:02.630
And it was not "The Martian."

00:05:02.630 --> 00:05:04.740
So, you may wonder why
you haven't heard of it.

00:05:04.740 --> 00:05:07.250
It's because it
wasn't very good.

00:05:07.250 --> 00:05:08.620
It was actually my second book.

00:05:08.620 --> 00:05:10.910
I wrote a book in
college that was

00:05:10.910 --> 00:05:13.470
so bad, even I knew it was bad.

00:05:13.470 --> 00:05:15.560
And it was before the
era of the internet,

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:18.120
so there are no digital
copies out there.

00:05:18.120 --> 00:05:19.750
No one will ever find it.

00:05:19.750 --> 00:05:22.880
There's only one physical
copy left that I know,

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:26.280
and my mother has it and
won't tell me where it is.

00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:29.190
Because she knows what'll
happen if she does.

00:05:29.190 --> 00:05:30.960
The second book,
I did post online.

00:05:30.960 --> 00:05:32.000
It was OK.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.750
The plot was decent,
but the prose was awful.

00:05:34.750 --> 00:05:37.090
And it's really awkward
to read, but you

00:05:37.090 --> 00:05:39.120
know it was my second pancake.

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:43.560
And, so, I had the
standard sad experience

00:05:43.560 --> 00:05:45.320
that all struggling
authors have.

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:46.370
Couldn't get an agent.

00:05:46.370 --> 00:05:48.450
Couldn't get a
publisher Interested.

00:05:48.450 --> 00:05:50.460
Just nobody was interested.

00:05:50.460 --> 00:05:53.350
And after three
years no success,

00:05:53.350 --> 00:05:55.310
I went back into the
software industry.

00:05:55.310 --> 00:05:57.350
Now this wasn't a
huge defeat for me,

00:05:57.350 --> 00:05:59.570
because I actually really
like programming computers.

00:05:59.570 --> 00:06:01.940
I've always-- I've always
enjoyed that aspect of my job.

00:06:01.940 --> 00:06:06.480
And I've always enjoyed the
high salary that comes with it.

00:06:06.480 --> 00:06:09.250
But I went back in
the programming.

00:06:09.250 --> 00:06:12.575
And around this time,
it's around 2002ish,

00:06:12.575 --> 00:06:15.790
and now the-- know the internet
is starting to really creep

00:06:15.790 --> 00:06:17.110
up and become more popular.

00:06:17.110 --> 00:06:19.094
Everyone's got an
internet connection.

00:06:19.094 --> 00:06:20.510
Everyone knows how
to use the web.

00:06:20.510 --> 00:06:22.380
And I thought, OK,
so what I'll do

00:06:22.380 --> 00:06:25.320
is I'll write stories
for fun and just

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:26.770
post them to a website.

00:06:26.770 --> 00:06:30.097
And I can-- that way I can get
an audience reading my stuff.

00:06:30.097 --> 00:06:32.180
And I don't need to make
a profession out of this.

00:06:32.180 --> 00:06:33.640
It'll just be a hobby.

00:06:33.640 --> 00:06:36.080
So that's what I did
for about 10 years.

00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:39.080
I made-- I started
out making web comics.

00:06:39.080 --> 00:06:41.850
I made a web comic called "Casey
and Andy," back in the day.

00:06:41.850 --> 00:06:44.230
And then another one
called "Chesire Crossing."

00:06:44.230 --> 00:06:47.510
And then I realized I'm A,
a terrible artist, in and B,

00:06:47.510 --> 00:06:48.730
I don't like doing art.

00:06:48.730 --> 00:06:52.270
So I went to writing short
fiction or long fiction,

00:06:52.270 --> 00:06:54.100
whatever, just
narrative fiction.

00:06:54.100 --> 00:06:56.660
And so I spent a lot
of time doing that.

00:06:56.660 --> 00:06:59.960
Just posting short stories
and serials to my website.

00:06:59.960 --> 00:07:01.710
I wrote one short
story called "The Egg"

00:07:01.710 --> 00:07:04.750
that was very popular, and
that brought a lot of people

00:07:04.750 --> 00:07:07.350
to my site and helped
build up a mailing list.

00:07:07.350 --> 00:07:09.810
And around the time I started
"The Martian," which was just

00:07:09.810 --> 00:07:11.880
a serial I was
posting to my website,

00:07:11.880 --> 00:07:14.550
I had about maybe
3,000 regular readers.

00:07:14.550 --> 00:07:17.260
But they were all science
minded dorks like myself.

00:07:17.260 --> 00:07:19.870
And, so, it was kind of cool,
because as I posted chapter

00:07:19.870 --> 00:07:23.440
by chapter, I posted a chapter
maybe every six to eight weeks,

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:25.320
they would email
and say, excuse me

00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:27.669
you got something
wrong on page 17.

00:07:27.669 --> 00:07:28.960
And, so, that was really handy.

00:07:28.960 --> 00:07:33.140
It was-- I called
them beta readers.

00:07:33.140 --> 00:07:35.990
So that process went
really smoothly.

00:07:35.990 --> 00:07:38.410
And it-- but it wasn't
some laser like focus.

00:07:38.410 --> 00:07:39.930
It was like sometimes
I'd go months

00:07:39.930 --> 00:07:41.130
without posting a chapter.

00:07:41.130 --> 00:07:43.200
It took me three years
to write the thing.

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:45.220
And I was working
on other serials

00:07:45.220 --> 00:07:46.650
and short stories of the time.

00:07:46.650 --> 00:07:48.930
So while I was writing "The
Martian," this hard sci-fi

00:07:48.930 --> 00:07:50.590
story about this man
stranded on Mars,

00:07:50.590 --> 00:07:53.480
I was also writing a story
about aliens invading earth,

00:07:53.480 --> 00:07:57.920
and a story about a mermaid in
the 19th century a New England.

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:01.270
So it's sort of an
eclectic group of stories.

00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:04.320
Anyway, so eventually I
finished "The Martian." and.

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:06.890
I thought, OK, I'm done,
moving on with life,

00:08:06.890 --> 00:08:08.020
on to other things.

00:08:08.020 --> 00:08:10.550
But I started to get email
from people saying, hey.

00:08:10.550 --> 00:08:12.050
I really enjoy "The
Martian," but I

00:08:12.050 --> 00:08:13.930
hate reading it on your
site, which is fair

00:08:13.930 --> 00:08:14.940
because my site is crap.

00:08:17.610 --> 00:08:19.207
Can you make an
e-reader version?

00:08:19.207 --> 00:08:20.540
So I figured out how to do that.

00:08:20.540 --> 00:08:22.584
I made an e-reader version,
an EPUB, and a MOBI.

00:08:22.584 --> 00:08:25.000
And I just posted them on the
site, and said there you go.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:26.880
Then I got another email
from people saying,

00:08:26.880 --> 00:08:28.980
hey I love your
story, hate your site.

00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:31.280
But I appreciate that
there's an e-reader version,

00:08:31.280 --> 00:08:32.840
but I'm not very
technically savvy.

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:35.340
And I don't know how to download
the thing from the internet

00:08:35.340 --> 00:08:36.940
and put it on the my e-reader.

00:08:36.940 --> 00:08:39.980
So, can you just post it
on Amazon or something.

00:08:39.980 --> 00:08:41.210
So I figured how to do that.

00:08:41.210 --> 00:08:41.751
And I did it.

00:08:41.751 --> 00:08:44.360
And it was pretty easy.

00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:47.680
It's KDP, Kindle
Direct Publishing.

00:08:47.680 --> 00:08:49.840
There's no initial cost outlay.

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:52.400
You just upload your
thing and you set a price.

00:08:52.400 --> 00:08:54.402
But you have to set a
price of at least $0.99,

00:08:54.402 --> 00:08:56.110
are not allowed to
give it away for free.

00:08:56.110 --> 00:08:58.070
It turns out Amazon
likes to make money.

00:08:58.070 --> 00:09:01.540
So, and you get a
percentage the royalties.

00:09:01.540 --> 00:09:04.885
And, so, I set the price
at the minimum $0.99,

00:09:04.885 --> 00:09:07.850
earning me a cool
$0.30 per copy.

00:09:07.850 --> 00:09:11.250
And told everybody all
right-- well, OK so first

00:09:11.250 --> 00:09:14.480
off you do that, you
post it, and then they

00:09:14.480 --> 00:09:16.640
hold onto it for
about 48 hours to have

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:18.050
an actual human look at it.

00:09:18.050 --> 00:09:20.300
Just to make sure you're
not posting a big goat porn

00:09:20.300 --> 00:09:20.800
compendium.

00:09:23.790 --> 00:09:25.140
Don't judge.

00:09:25.140 --> 00:09:30.520
So, then once it's for
sale I posted to everybody.

00:09:30.520 --> 00:09:31.950
I said, OK, here you go.

00:09:31.950 --> 00:09:33.410
You can read on
my site for free.

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:36.330
You can download the e-reader
version from my site for free.

00:09:36.330 --> 00:09:39.480
Or you can pay Amazon a buck
to put it on your Kindle, which

00:09:39.480 --> 00:09:40.810
is basically what you're doing.

00:09:40.810 --> 00:09:43.310
And more people paid the
buck than anything else.

00:09:43.310 --> 00:09:46.470
They really-- it
just goes to show you

00:09:46.470 --> 00:09:49.482
the reach that Amazon has
into the readership market,

00:09:49.482 --> 00:09:51.190
and that people are
willing to pay a buck

00:09:51.190 --> 00:09:53.420
to avoid technical hassles.

00:09:53.420 --> 00:09:54.837
So it started to
sell really well.

00:09:54.837 --> 00:09:57.128
And it started working its
way up the top sellers list,

00:09:57.128 --> 00:09:58.490
in various categories in Amazon.

00:09:58.490 --> 00:10:01.450
Got Gone up into the
top 10 of sci-fi.

00:10:01.450 --> 00:10:04.060
Got up into number one in
sci-fi, into the top 20

00:10:04.060 --> 00:10:05.134
in all Kindle.

00:10:05.134 --> 00:10:06.550
And, so, that's
when things really

00:10:06.550 --> 00:10:08.190
start to snowball, right.

00:10:08.190 --> 00:10:10.437
Because now you've
got people going,

00:10:10.437 --> 00:10:11.520
oh, I want to read a book.

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:12.080
I don't know.

00:10:12.080 --> 00:10:14.251
Whats-- I feel like sci-fi.

00:10:14.251 --> 00:10:15.500
What are the top 10 in sci-fi?

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:16.740
I'll pick one of those.

00:10:16.740 --> 00:10:18.640
So you get this--
a lot of exposure

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:20.340
by being on those lists.

00:10:20.340 --> 00:10:22.980
And so the sales really
went through the roof.

00:10:22.980 --> 00:10:25.185
And I didn't realize
how well they

00:10:25.185 --> 00:10:27.310
were selling, because I
had no experience with self

00:10:27.310 --> 00:10:28.190
publishing.

00:10:28.190 --> 00:10:30.490
I looked at my sales
and I was like, huh,

00:10:30.490 --> 00:10:32.470
I'm selling about
500 units a day.

00:10:32.470 --> 00:10:33.870
Is that good?

00:10:33.870 --> 00:10:34.660
I don't know.

00:10:34.660 --> 00:10:35.740
It's self publishing.

00:10:35.740 --> 00:10:37.320
It seems like it's good.

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:38.300
I can't tell.

00:10:38.300 --> 00:10:41.660
And then-- but
what's funny is when

00:10:41.660 --> 00:10:44.620
you submit to KDP you
automatically become

00:10:44.620 --> 00:10:47.230
part of this forum, where you
can talk to other authors.

00:10:47.230 --> 00:10:49.313
And, so there's this forum
where other authors are

00:10:49.313 --> 00:10:51.830
talking about their books and
how to market their books.

00:10:51.830 --> 00:10:53.746
And there are threads
where they say,

00:10:53.746 --> 00:10:54.870
tell us your sales numbers.

00:10:54.870 --> 00:10:56.430
Everybody post
your sales numbers.

00:10:56.430 --> 00:10:59.190
And people are like, I
sold five copies today man.

00:10:59.190 --> 00:11:00.110
That's awesome.

00:11:00.110 --> 00:11:01.600
Hurray for Christmas rush.

00:11:01.600 --> 00:11:04.390
And I'm like, I sold 500.

00:11:04.390 --> 00:11:07.550
I guess that's pretty good.

00:11:07.550 --> 00:11:10.690
So anyway, eventually, I
didn't know this was going on.

00:11:10.690 --> 00:11:12.690
But it got the attention
of Random House,

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:14.290
or actually
specifically by Crown.

00:11:14.290 --> 00:11:16.039
If you look at your
free copies you'll see

00:11:16.039 --> 00:11:17.850
is published by Crown
Publishing, which

00:11:17.850 --> 00:11:19.730
is a division of Random House.

00:11:19.730 --> 00:11:23.040
And at the time there's an
editor at Random House name

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:26.200
Julian Pavia, and
he was re-- he had

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:27.390
the book recommended to him.

00:11:27.390 --> 00:11:30.000
He'd heard about it and he saw
it was doing well on Amazon.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.200
And he thought,
should I read this.

00:11:32.200 --> 00:11:32.967
I don't know.

00:11:32.967 --> 00:11:35.050
Is it something that would
have mainstream appeal,

00:11:35.050 --> 00:11:36.700
or is it just engineer porn.

00:11:36.700 --> 00:11:38.310
It's not clear.

00:11:38.310 --> 00:11:40.690
And so he said-- he was
talking to a colleague of his,

00:11:40.690 --> 00:11:42.540
a literary agent
named David Fugate.

00:11:42.540 --> 00:11:45.230
And he said, I'm not sure if
I want to read this or not.

00:11:45.230 --> 00:11:47.684
And David said well,
I'll read it and let

00:11:47.684 --> 00:11:48.600
you know what I think.

00:11:48.600 --> 00:11:49.420
And he's all right.

00:11:49.420 --> 00:11:51.300
So David read it
and he liked it.

00:11:51.300 --> 00:11:54.300
And he came and said hey,
you want an agent, to me.

00:11:54.300 --> 00:11:56.250
And, so, after three
years of not being

00:11:56.250 --> 00:11:59.460
able to even-- after three
years of just constant rejection

00:11:59.460 --> 00:12:02.480
by agents, now later in life,
I have one knocking at my door.

00:12:02.480 --> 00:12:03.430
Which was pretty cool.

00:12:03.430 --> 00:12:05.370
And, so, I did some
research on him,

00:12:05.370 --> 00:12:07.020
make sure he was a real person.

00:12:07.020 --> 00:12:11.010
And then said sure and he's
like-- and he's like alright.

00:12:11.010 --> 00:12:13.260
So Julian, how much you going
to pay us for this book.

00:12:16.630 --> 00:12:19.970
So he was-- he negotiated
the book deal with Jillian.

00:12:19.970 --> 00:12:22.600
And then while
that was going on,

00:12:22.600 --> 00:12:25.820
20th Century Fox came
for the film rights,

00:12:25.820 --> 00:12:27.680
which is interesting, right.

00:12:27.680 --> 00:12:30.890
And those two negotiations
were going on at the same time.

00:12:30.890 --> 00:12:33.960
And both of them were--
both negotiations

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:36.320
were completed four days apart.

00:12:36.320 --> 00:12:38.030
So that was a very
eventful week for me.

00:12:38.030 --> 00:12:41.900
I got a print deal and a
movie deal in one week.

00:12:41.900 --> 00:12:44.850
So I was-- I had to take a
day off there just to go home

00:12:44.850 --> 00:12:46.450
and lay down.

00:12:46.450 --> 00:12:48.690
I was so worked
up, and stressed,

00:12:48.690 --> 00:12:49.860
and anxious it was horrible.

00:12:49.860 --> 00:12:52.960
I got-- I couldn't breathe.

00:12:52.960 --> 00:12:56.750
So anyway, the print
deal came together.

00:12:56.750 --> 00:12:59.070
We did some minor
editing on the book,

00:12:59.070 --> 00:13:01.459
because of course once
a publisher gets it

00:13:01.459 --> 00:13:02.750
they want to make some changes.

00:13:02.750 --> 00:13:05.560
But pretty minor in the
grand scheme of things.

00:13:05.560 --> 00:13:07.370
No substantive plot changes.

00:13:07.370 --> 00:13:10.442
Just hey Andy, you got a little
excited in this section here.

00:13:10.442 --> 00:13:12.150
You have people talking
but never tell us

00:13:12.150 --> 00:13:14.080
what room they're in
or what's going on.

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:16.210
It's just a bunch of
floating dialogue.

00:13:16.210 --> 00:13:17.300
That sort of thing.

00:13:17.300 --> 00:13:20.026
And, hey Andy, nobody
anywhere understands

00:13:20.026 --> 00:13:22.400
what you were saying in this
paragraph of technical crap,

00:13:22.400 --> 00:13:26.197
so simplify it.

00:13:26.197 --> 00:13:27.280
And then they released it.

00:13:27.280 --> 00:13:31.370
And it was-- in its
first week of sales

00:13:31.370 --> 00:13:34.190
went straight to the
best seller list.

00:13:34.190 --> 00:13:36.770
So it really did very well.

00:13:36.770 --> 00:13:39.730
And at the time
the movie rights--

00:13:39.730 --> 00:13:42.850
so the way movie rights
deals work is it's

00:13:42.850 --> 00:13:45.956
not just some guy drives
up in a limousine,

00:13:45.956 --> 00:13:47.580
hand you a pile of
money, and then they

00:13:47.580 --> 00:13:49.750
go make a movie, right.

00:13:49.750 --> 00:13:52.910
It's a little more complicated.

00:13:52.910 --> 00:13:55.470
So the first thing they do
is they secure the option.

00:13:55.470 --> 00:13:57.777
So they're not actually
buying the rights yet.

00:13:57.777 --> 00:14:00.110
What they're doing is giving
you a small amount of money

00:14:00.110 --> 00:14:03.100
to be the only studio that
is allowed to buy the rights.

00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:05.180
So they're securing
the exclusive option

00:14:05.180 --> 00:14:06.400
to buy the rights.

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:07.697
So you work out the whole deal.

00:14:07.697 --> 00:14:09.530
You work out the whole
rights purchase deal.

00:14:09.530 --> 00:14:12.730
It was a 34 page contract that
I had to sign and notarize

00:14:12.730 --> 00:14:14.669
in four places.

00:14:14.669 --> 00:14:16.335
You work out that
whole deal in advance.

00:14:16.335 --> 00:14:17.950
Saying, here's a
big pile of money

00:14:17.950 --> 00:14:19.984
we're going to give you
if we buy the rights.

00:14:19.984 --> 00:14:21.650
And here's a part the
contract that says

00:14:21.650 --> 00:14:22.960
only we can buy the rights.

00:14:22.960 --> 00:14:25.160
And here's a small pile
of money that we give you,

00:14:25.160 --> 00:14:28.789
so that you're willing to
agree to this option deal.

00:14:28.789 --> 00:14:30.580
And so they give you
a small pile of money.

00:14:30.580 --> 00:14:34.015
Then they have 18 months
to activate the contract.

00:14:34.015 --> 00:14:35.640
And they can just
activate the contract

00:14:35.640 --> 00:14:37.480
by sending you the
big pile of money.

00:14:37.480 --> 00:14:39.910
And if they don't
activate the contract,

00:14:39.910 --> 00:14:42.130
then the rights
devolve back to me,

00:14:42.130 --> 00:14:44.380
and I get to keep
that small amount.

00:14:44.380 --> 00:14:45.930
So that's how options work.

00:14:45.930 --> 00:14:48.481
And they don't activate
until they are absolutely

00:14:48.481 --> 00:14:50.980
sure they need to do it, because
it's a fair amount of money

00:14:50.980 --> 00:14:52.688
and they don't want
to just piss it away.

00:14:52.688 --> 00:14:56.310
So they actually only activated
the rights contract the day

00:14:56.310 --> 00:14:59.270
they started filming.

00:14:59.270 --> 00:15:01.595
So it's the moment--
and the reason

00:15:01.595 --> 00:15:02.970
is because that's
the moment when

00:15:02.970 --> 00:15:05.150
they have now generated
intellectual property

00:15:05.150 --> 00:15:05.710
based on it.

00:15:05.710 --> 00:15:09.590
And they're like, well, now we
need to make sure we own it.

00:15:09.590 --> 00:15:13.230
So anyway watching that
process unfold was fascinating,

00:15:13.230 --> 00:15:17.910
because I didn't-- at the
beginning everybody told,

00:15:17.910 --> 00:15:20.040
they literary agent,
my film agent,

00:15:20.040 --> 00:15:22.180
everybody in the
industry told me,

00:15:22.180 --> 00:15:25.500
don't get excited about
people buying a movie option.

00:15:25.500 --> 00:15:29.601
The studios by several hundred
options for every actual movie

00:15:29.601 --> 00:15:30.100
they make.

00:15:30.100 --> 00:15:32.570
You have a less than 1%
chance of this actually being

00:15:32.570 --> 00:15:33.342
greenlighted.

00:15:33.342 --> 00:15:34.300
So don't get worked up.

00:15:34.300 --> 00:15:37.920
Just enjoy the money that they
gave you and call it a day.

00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:40.650
But then they got
Drew Goddard on board.

00:15:40.650 --> 00:15:43.450
Drew Goddard is veteran
screenwriter and director.

00:15:43.450 --> 00:15:44.970
He directed "Cabin
in the Woods."

00:15:44.970 --> 00:15:47.680
He wrote "Cloverfield"
and a bunch of episodes

00:15:47.680 --> 00:15:49.890
of "Lost" and Buffy."

00:15:49.890 --> 00:15:53.650
He is the creator and
writer of the new Netflix

00:15:53.650 --> 00:15:55.150
"Daredevil" series.

00:15:55.150 --> 00:15:56.800
So he's a veteran.

00:15:56.800 --> 00:15:58.190
And he really liked the book.

00:15:58.190 --> 00:15:59.900
And so he wrote a screenplay.

00:15:59.900 --> 00:16:02.260
He said I want to
write and direct this.

00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:04.990
So the studio FOX was
like, sure, sounds good.

00:16:04.990 --> 00:16:07.270
Write a script and
we'll take a look.

00:16:07.270 --> 00:16:09.100
So he wrote a screenplay.

00:16:09.100 --> 00:16:11.589
And then he was set
to write and direct.

00:16:11.589 --> 00:16:13.380
And they're like, well,
we have a director,

00:16:13.380 --> 00:16:14.950
but we need an actor.

00:16:14.950 --> 00:16:16.770
We need someone to
take an interest

00:16:16.770 --> 00:16:18.030
in playing the lead role.

00:16:18.030 --> 00:16:20.239
This movie is not-- we're
not willing to make it

00:16:20.239 --> 00:16:21.530
with a nobody in the lead role.

00:16:21.530 --> 00:16:23.210
It has to be a big name.

00:16:23.210 --> 00:16:24.970
And, so, right
around that time then

00:16:24.970 --> 00:16:27.670
Matt Damon expressed
interest in playing the lead.

00:16:27.670 --> 00:16:31.782
And, so, the studio
is like, oh really.

00:16:31.782 --> 00:16:33.990
And they start taking a
project a lot more seriously.

00:16:33.990 --> 00:16:37.635
They're like, OK, now we've
got a veteran director

00:16:37.635 --> 00:16:41.650
and a the top tier well
known actor to play the lead.

00:16:41.650 --> 00:16:44.910
And then Sony came along
and offered Drew Goddard

00:16:44.910 --> 00:16:47.079
the director's chair for
the new "Spiderman" movie.

00:16:47.079 --> 00:16:48.870
And he's like, sorry
guys I got to do that.

00:16:48.870 --> 00:16:50.130
This is a dream come true.

00:16:50.130 --> 00:16:51.930
So he left to go work on that.

00:16:51.930 --> 00:16:54.070
But he's like,
enjoy my screenplay.

00:16:54.070 --> 00:16:56.691
And that makes it
sound mercenary.

00:16:56.691 --> 00:16:58.440
He was-- he's really
invested in a project

00:16:58.440 --> 00:16:59.690
and he kept working
on it the whole time,

00:16:59.690 --> 00:17:01.390
but he's like I'm
not going to direct.

00:17:01.390 --> 00:17:04.810
So, he goes off to direct
the next "Spiderman" movie.

00:17:04.810 --> 00:17:07.660
And then-- now the
studio is like, aah.

00:17:07.660 --> 00:17:09.291
We had a director and a star.

00:17:09.291 --> 00:17:11.040
Well, first we had a
director and no star,

00:17:11.040 --> 00:17:12.660
now we have a star no director.

00:17:12.660 --> 00:17:14.470
And then Ridley Scott
said, I'll direct it,

00:17:14.470 --> 00:17:17.829
and they said, oh really?

00:17:17.829 --> 00:17:19.859
So once they have
Ridley Scott on board

00:17:19.859 --> 00:17:22.190
to direct and Matt
Damon on board to star

00:17:22.190 --> 00:17:24.790
that's pretty much when they
made the decision that they're

00:17:24.790 --> 00:17:26.079
definitely going to do this.

00:17:26.079 --> 00:17:28.319
Although I didn't know that.

00:17:28.319 --> 00:17:30.200
To me it just seemed,
well, this looks good.

00:17:32.884 --> 00:17:35.050
And then everything else
started to fall into place.

00:17:35.050 --> 00:17:37.633
The studio was like, OK, we are
going to sink a bunch of money

00:17:37.633 --> 00:17:38.210
into this.

00:17:38.210 --> 00:17:40.790
If we're going to green
light it, we'll go big.

00:17:40.790 --> 00:17:44.070
And then, also a bunch of
big name actors and actresses

00:17:44.070 --> 00:17:46.530
took an interest in the
project, because it's

00:17:46.530 --> 00:17:48.745
Matt Damon and Ridley Scott
in a big budget movie,

00:17:48.745 --> 00:17:50.270
and it'll be heavily marketed.

00:17:50.270 --> 00:17:52.600
And they like being in
those sorts of things.

00:17:52.600 --> 00:17:55.860
So then they started
to get all these really

00:17:55.860 --> 00:17:58.520
big name actors and actresses
interested in playing roles

00:17:58.520 --> 00:17:59.260
in the movie.

00:17:59.260 --> 00:18:01.320
And they were like,
well, this is super,

00:18:01.320 --> 00:18:04.200
but there's just no way
we can afford all of you.

00:18:04.200 --> 00:18:04.986
There's no way.

00:18:04.986 --> 00:18:06.610
If we paid all of
you what you're worth

00:18:06.610 --> 00:18:08.080
this movie would cost $400.

00:18:08.080 --> 00:18:09.950
Million We can't do it.

00:18:09.950 --> 00:18:12.370
And they just-- a lot
of them just agreed

00:18:12.370 --> 00:18:14.930
to do it for less than
they would normally

00:18:14.930 --> 00:18:17.250
get just because they
really liked the story.

00:18:17.250 --> 00:18:20.040
So that's why that
cast is ridiculous.

00:18:20.040 --> 00:18:23.410
It stars Matt Damon, Jessica
Chastain, Sebastian Stan,

00:18:23.410 --> 00:18:28.090
Kate Mara, missing,
missing one of the crew.

00:18:28.090 --> 00:18:30.690
Oh Michael Pena,
and Aksel Hennie,

00:18:30.690 --> 00:18:32.160
which most people
don't know him.

00:18:32.160 --> 00:18:33.680
Meanwhile on earth,
the roles are

00:18:33.680 --> 00:18:35.290
played by Chiwetel
Ejiofor, who you

00:18:35.290 --> 00:18:37.710
may know from "12 Years a
Slave," or maybe this crowd

00:18:37.710 --> 00:18:43.970
might know him best from the bad
guy from the movie "Serenity."

00:18:43.970 --> 00:18:51.076
And Kristen Wiig, Donald
Glover, AKA "Childish Gambino."

00:18:51.076 --> 00:18:52.690
Hey, for those of
you under wrap,

00:18:52.690 --> 00:18:55.830
you might know him by that
name and not the other one.

00:18:55.830 --> 00:19:01.850
Let's see, who else is
on Earth, Jeff Daniels.

00:19:01.850 --> 00:19:03.319
Yeah, it just goes on and on.

00:19:03.319 --> 00:19:04.610
It's just this ridiculous cast.

00:19:04.610 --> 00:19:07.030
I'm sure I missed people too.

00:19:07.030 --> 00:19:10.000
But, so, they got this
cast and then, yeah.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:11.470
They started
shooting in November.

00:19:11.470 --> 00:19:14.780
They finished shooting
in March, and now they're

00:19:14.780 --> 00:19:16.930
doing post production
and test screening.

00:19:16.930 --> 00:19:20.410
The test screenings have
been going very, very well.

00:19:20.410 --> 00:19:22.090
The audiences are
really liking it,

00:19:22.090 --> 00:19:24.420
so it's looking like it'll
be a really good movie.

00:19:24.420 --> 00:19:28.166
And I got to see it on Friday,
just two-- a few days ago.

00:19:28.166 --> 00:19:29.540
That's actually
why I'm down here

00:19:29.540 --> 00:19:32.050
in Southern California,
because I went to FOX

00:19:32.050 --> 00:19:33.150
and I got to watch it.

00:19:33.150 --> 00:19:35.790
And I was really psyched because
I get my own title placard.

00:19:35.790 --> 00:19:38.140
It's up on the movie, "based
on the novel by Andy Weir,"

00:19:38.140 --> 00:19:39.610
and no other text on the screen.

00:19:43.990 --> 00:19:46.547
So, now the first
question I always get,

00:19:46.547 --> 00:19:48.380
so I'll just go ahead
and pre-answer it now.

00:19:48.380 --> 00:19:50.630
Hey Andy, what was your
involvement in the movie?

00:19:50.630 --> 00:19:52.230
So I'll go ahead
and answer that now.

00:19:52.230 --> 00:19:55.830
My main job on the film
was to cash the check.

00:19:55.830 --> 00:19:58.080
I did that very well I feel.

00:19:58.080 --> 00:20:00.360
I mean just smoothly.

00:20:00.360 --> 00:20:02.807
They didn't have any--
they have no requirement

00:20:02.807 --> 00:20:03.890
to involve me in anything.

00:20:03.890 --> 00:20:06.570
They don't need to
consult me in any way.

00:20:06.570 --> 00:20:08.090
The only thing
that's in my contract

00:20:08.090 --> 00:20:11.150
is they're going to give me
money, and then way later on I

00:20:11.150 --> 00:20:12.790
get to go to the premiere.

00:20:12.790 --> 00:20:14.309
That's it.

00:20:14.309 --> 00:20:15.850
They don't need to
consult me at all.

00:20:15.850 --> 00:20:18.580
But they chose to involve
me, so that was really cool.

00:20:18.580 --> 00:20:21.400
Drew called me a
lot, frequently when

00:20:21.400 --> 00:20:22.970
he was writing the screenplay.

00:20:22.970 --> 00:20:23.810
He's a super guy.

00:20:23.810 --> 00:20:24.690
He's really friendly.

00:20:24.690 --> 00:20:26.110
And in fact,
immediately after this,

00:20:26.110 --> 00:20:27.651
I'm going to go have
drinks with him.

00:20:30.500 --> 00:20:32.910
He called me a lot,
because he really wanted

00:20:32.910 --> 00:20:34.780
to stay true to the novel.

00:20:34.780 --> 00:20:38.390
And then he sent revs
of the screenplay,

00:20:38.390 --> 00:20:40.100
and got my feedback on it.

00:20:40.100 --> 00:20:43.289
He made some changes based
on one on my feedback,

00:20:43.289 --> 00:20:44.830
and ignored other
things, which fine.

00:20:44.830 --> 00:20:46.450
It's his screenplay.

00:20:46.450 --> 00:20:48.070
And then, while they
were filming it,

00:20:48.070 --> 00:20:49.900
I would get these
questions filtered

00:20:49.900 --> 00:20:54.700
through four intermediaries
from Ridley Scott.

00:20:54.700 --> 00:20:57.090
And I could tell
from the questions

00:20:57.090 --> 00:20:58.830
that he was asking
that he really

00:20:58.830 --> 00:21:01.530
cared about technical
and scientific accuracy.

00:21:01.530 --> 00:21:03.970
I mean one of the questions
that came through was,

00:21:03.970 --> 00:21:08.720
he said, OK, can we show
Mark pouring hydrazine

00:21:08.720 --> 00:21:12.030
from one container into another,
out on the surface of Mars.

00:21:12.030 --> 00:21:13.464
He's wearing his
EVA suit and he's

00:21:13.464 --> 00:21:15.010
pouring it from one
container to the other.

00:21:15.010 --> 00:21:16.970
And I'm like, no, hydrazine
is really volatile

00:21:16.970 --> 00:21:19.550
and in Mars atmospheric
pressure it would boil off.

00:21:19.550 --> 00:21:21.800
And he's like, OK, then
we're not going to do it.

00:21:21.800 --> 00:21:26.170
And so it's that level of
technical double checking, led

00:21:26.170 --> 00:21:28.440
me to believe, OK, they're
really being accurate.

00:21:28.440 --> 00:21:30.565
And then, of course, a few
