00:29:08.810 --> 00:29:12.000
It should take you a
long time to read it.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:15.560
But you've gotta resist
that urge to overdo it

00:29:15.560 --> 00:29:16.810
and show your work.

00:29:16.810 --> 00:29:18.960
One thing I did was
I wrote software

00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:20.760
to calculate the
orbital trajectories

00:29:20.760 --> 00:29:22.830
that they take on their
ship from Earth to Mars.

00:29:22.830 --> 00:29:24.540
Those are all real.

00:29:24.540 --> 00:29:27.140
And it was hard,
because I kind of have

00:29:27.140 --> 00:29:28.470
an interest in normal dynamics.

00:29:28.470 --> 00:29:29.860
It's actually
really simple math.

00:29:29.860 --> 00:29:31.620
It's not really complicated.

00:29:31.620 --> 00:29:34.650
But it gets insanely
complicated when

00:29:34.650 --> 00:29:37.150
you have a ship that
constantly accelerates.

00:29:37.150 --> 00:29:39.080
So their ship uses
ion propulsion.

00:29:39.080 --> 00:29:42.600
So it has a very slow constant
acceleration of two millimeters

00:29:42.600 --> 00:29:43.820
per second per second.

00:29:43.820 --> 00:29:47.130
That's it, but it can do
it constantly for months.

00:29:47.130 --> 00:29:50.190
And so once I was
about 10 integrals in,

00:29:50.190 --> 00:29:53.752
in my gigantic page full
of formulas, You know what?

00:29:53.752 --> 00:29:55.210
I'm not going to
work out this way.

00:29:55.210 --> 00:29:56.690
But I'm a computer programmer.

00:29:56.690 --> 00:29:58.820
So when the only tool
you have is a hammer,

00:29:58.820 --> 00:30:00.950
every problem starts
to look like a nail.

00:30:00.950 --> 00:30:03.160
And, so, I'm going to do
this through brute force

00:30:03.160 --> 00:30:04.300
and simulation.

00:30:04.300 --> 00:30:07.600
So I wrote software to work it
out and try different things,

00:30:07.600 --> 00:30:10.700
until I found the
course that they would

00:30:10.700 --> 00:30:12.532
take to get from Earth to Mars.

00:30:12.532 --> 00:30:14.240
Which also required
me to choose a launch

00:30:14.240 --> 00:30:16.430
window that would work.

00:30:16.430 --> 00:30:18.550
And I had the
additional limitation

00:30:18.550 --> 00:30:21.000
of the launch window
had to work such

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:24.280
that, while they were on Mars,
Thanksgiving of that year

00:30:24.280 --> 00:30:24.960
would happen.

00:30:24.960 --> 00:30:26.070
During that period.

00:30:26.070 --> 00:30:27.780
For plot reasons, I needed that.

00:30:27.780 --> 00:30:31.600
And, so, OK, I need to calculate
a constantly accelerating

00:30:31.600 --> 00:30:37.020
orbital trajectory that gets to
Mars such that within 31 days

00:30:37.020 --> 00:30:38.540
there'll be Thanksgiving.

00:30:38.540 --> 00:30:41.320
And it has to happen at
least 20 years in the future

00:30:41.320 --> 00:30:44.600
to be plausible, and I don't
want me to far in the future.

00:30:44.600 --> 00:30:50.010
Anyway July 7, 2035.

00:30:50.010 --> 00:30:55.240
Anyway, so, I would say I spent
at least half to 3/4 of my time

00:30:55.240 --> 00:30:56.550
doing research.

