00:39:46.150 --> 00:39:48.136
AUDIENCE: The least plausible.

00:39:48.136 --> 00:39:49.390
They're all very implausible.

00:39:49.390 --> 00:39:49.900
ANDY WEIR: Yeah.

00:39:49.900 --> 00:39:50.460
Well.

00:39:50.460 --> 00:39:54.020
OK, so there are two
places where I deliberately

00:39:54.020 --> 00:39:57.770
violated physics in
reality for plot purposes.

00:39:57.770 --> 00:40:01.090
Number one, the biggest one is
the sandstorm at the beginning.

00:40:01.090 --> 00:40:06.450
In reality Mars' atmosphere
is 0.6% as in about one two

00:40:06.450 --> 00:40:09.130
hundredth, the density
of Earth's atmosphere.

00:40:09.130 --> 00:40:11.610
So it's extremely,
extremely thin.

00:40:11.610 --> 00:40:13.870
And yes they do get
sandstorms on-- they.

00:40:13.870 --> 00:40:15.570
You know those Martians.

00:40:15.570 --> 00:40:19.410
Mars does get sandstorms
150 kilometers an hour.

00:40:19.410 --> 00:40:23.850
But with the air so thin the
inertia of the sandstorms

00:40:23.850 --> 00:40:24.990
is extremely low.

00:40:24.990 --> 00:40:27.120
It's like being in about
one kilometer an hour

00:40:27.120 --> 00:40:28.320
breeze on earth.

00:40:28.320 --> 00:40:29.720
It wouldn't knock over anything.

00:40:29.720 --> 00:40:31.020
It wouldn't damage anything.

00:40:31.020 --> 00:40:33.240
It wouldn't hurt anything.

00:40:33.240 --> 00:40:35.440
I came up with an alternate
scenario in the story

00:40:35.440 --> 00:40:40.580
where it turns out, oh, OK--
I had it where they're doing

00:40:40.580 --> 00:40:41.830
and MAV engine test.

00:40:41.830 --> 00:40:43.820
And there's an explosion
during that process.

00:40:43.820 --> 00:40:45.600
And that's what causes
all the problems.

00:40:45.600 --> 00:40:47.527
And I had ways to force
them to the lift off.

00:40:47.527 --> 00:40:49.360
And think Mark was dead,
and all that stuff.

00:40:49.360 --> 00:40:52.150
But it just didn't feel
right, it didn't feel as good.

00:40:52.150 --> 00:40:53.590
And in a man versus
nature story,

00:40:53.590 --> 00:40:55.680
I wanted nature to get
the first punch in.

00:40:55.680 --> 00:40:59.820
And, so it worked out
for the 99.9% of people

00:40:59.820 --> 00:41:03.510
who don't know about the
realities of Mara' atmosphere,

00:41:03.510 --> 00:41:05.570
there's a real
general public idea

00:41:05.570 --> 00:41:07.660
that Martian dust
storms are this--

00:41:07.660 --> 00:41:09.410
are like Earth sandstorms.

00:41:09.410 --> 00:41:10.780
So I played into that.

00:41:10.780 --> 00:41:15.030
The other deliberate thing
I did was-- the violation

00:41:15.030 --> 00:41:18.430
of the reality I did was, I
just have this one paragraph

00:41:18.430 --> 00:41:20.930
somewhere in the middle of the
book where he says, oh, yeah,

00:41:20.930 --> 00:41:22.640
the HABs, and the
rovers, and EVA suits

00:41:22.640 --> 00:41:25.784
are all radiation shielded.

00:41:25.784 --> 00:41:26.760
OK.

00:41:26.760 --> 00:41:29.930
There's no such material
that can do that,

00:41:29.930 --> 00:41:31.700
that casually or that easily.

00:41:31.700 --> 00:41:35.160
He has this thin, flexible,
airtight material,

00:41:35.160 --> 00:41:38.097
it's about that thick that
will block all the radiation,

00:41:38.097 --> 00:41:40.180
or brings the radiation
levels inside the HAB down

00:41:40.180 --> 00:41:41.530
to Earth normal.

00:41:41.530 --> 00:41:42.780
And you just can't do that.

00:41:42.780 --> 00:41:45.430
You would actually need
several centimeters of lead,

00:41:45.430 --> 00:41:48.910
or 10 centimeters of
water, or a meter of rock

00:41:48.910 --> 00:41:51.200
to get the radiation
levels down to what we

00:41:51.200 --> 00:41:52.660
have on the surface of Earth.

00:41:52.660 --> 00:41:55.987
Because Earth has a big
strong magnetic field and also

00:41:55.987 --> 00:41:57.820
a big thick atmosphere
to stop the radiation

00:41:57.820 --> 00:41:58.611
from getting to us.

00:41:58.611 --> 00:41:59.930
And Mars has neither.

00:41:59.930 --> 00:42:01.590
So that was another
thing that I didn't

00:42:01.590 --> 00:42:02.640
want to deal with,
because I knew

00:42:02.640 --> 00:42:04.340
he was going to be
out on the surface

00:42:04.340 --> 00:42:06.514
doing all these makeshift
solutions, lots of stuff.

00:42:06.514 --> 00:42:07.930
And I didn't want
to say, oh, yeah

00:42:07.930 --> 00:42:10.450
and then he dies of cancer.

00:42:10.450 --> 00:42:17.860
So-- so that was
some hand wavy stuff.

00:42:17.860 --> 00:42:21.090
So some things I
got wrong by mistake

00:42:21.090 --> 00:42:23.410
are the water thing that
I just talked about.

00:42:23.410 --> 00:42:26.700
And then one of them is really,
really obscure, but I liked it.

00:42:26.700 --> 00:42:29.300
A chemist emailed me after
the book was out in print,

00:42:29.300 --> 00:42:30.550
so I couldn't change anything.

00:42:30.550 --> 00:42:33.510
He's like, OK, you told
me how much hydrazine Mark

00:42:33.510 --> 00:42:34.930
reduced in the HAB.

00:42:34.930 --> 00:42:38.240
You told me how much and
how long he took to do it.

00:42:38.240 --> 00:42:40.220
You gave information
elsewhere in the book

00:42:40.220 --> 00:42:42.110
about the internal
volume of a HAB,

00:42:42.110 --> 00:42:44.760
and what the atmospheric
makeup is of the HAB.

00:42:44.760 --> 00:42:47.140
And so this gives me
enough information

00:42:47.140 --> 00:42:50.720
to calculate how much the
temperature inside the HAB

00:42:50.720 --> 00:42:53.640
is going to go up,
do that chemistry.

00:42:53.640 --> 00:42:54.885
It's 400 degrees Celsius.

00:42:57.610 --> 00:42:59.470
I could have solved
that one pretty easily,

00:42:59.470 --> 00:43:01.597
if I'd known about it.

00:43:01.597 --> 00:43:03.680
But anyway, so those are
the few the inaccuracies.

00:43:03.680 --> 00:43:06.430
But, I think, you're asking
what is the biggest inaccuracy?

00:43:06.430 --> 00:43:09.220
The biggest inaccuracy is that
a mission that size would get

00:43:09.220 --> 00:43:11.896
funded at all.

00:43:11.896 --> 00:43:14.890
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:43:14.890 --> 00:43:16.840
AUDIENCE: So, one more.

00:43:16.840 --> 00:43:20.134
This isn't particularly--
I don't particularly

00:43:20.134 --> 00:43:21.800
have a well formed
question around this.

00:43:21.800 --> 00:43:24.430
It's just one thing that kept
striking me over and over as I

00:43:24.430 --> 00:43:27.550
was reading the book is this
is a man versus nature story,

00:43:27.550 --> 00:43:28.840
as you were just alluding to.

00:43:28.840 --> 00:43:30.510
And those are really
all that common.

00:43:30.510 --> 00:43:34.010
You see a lot more
inter-personal conflicts,

00:43:34.010 --> 00:43:37.120
man versus man or whatever, in
terms of these gross categories

00:43:37.120 --> 00:43:37.950
of stories.

00:43:37.950 --> 00:43:39.430
Is this-- I guess
my question would

00:43:39.430 --> 00:43:41.260
be, is this kind of your
favorite sort of thing

00:43:41.260 --> 00:43:41.759
to write?

00:43:41.759 --> 00:43:44.720
Did you find this
to be fruitful?

00:43:44.720 --> 00:43:47.380
Just what was your feeling on
writing that kind of story?

00:43:47.380 --> 00:43:48.720
ANDY WEIR: I really enjoyed it.

00:43:48.720 --> 00:43:51.430
And I do love man
versus nature stories.

00:43:51.430 --> 00:43:57.970
Because it's really just a
veiled way of saying science!

00:43:57.970 --> 00:43:58.470
Right.

00:43:58.470 --> 00:44:01.220
Because that's what man versus
nature really is, right.

00:44:01.220 --> 00:44:03.160
I mean-- and the
other thing I like

00:44:03.160 --> 00:44:05.660
about it is, I don't
know about other people,

00:44:05.660 --> 00:44:10.280
but when I'm watching a story
with a central plot conflict,

00:44:10.280 --> 00:44:12.070
with a protagonist
and an antagonist.

00:44:12.070 --> 00:44:14.840
A part of me, no matter,
how bad he is, a part of me

00:44:14.840 --> 00:44:16.680
roots for the antagonist.

00:44:16.680 --> 00:44:19.430
Because first off I know
that in almost all stories

00:44:19.430 --> 00:44:21.970
the antagonist is
destined to fail.

00:44:21.970 --> 00:44:24.180
And so I kind of
feel sorry for him.

00:44:24.180 --> 00:44:25.180
And I'm rooting for him.

00:44:25.180 --> 00:44:27.280
Also usually the antagonist
is the prime mover.

00:44:27.280 --> 00:44:29.890
The antagonist is, I'm the
villain who's robbing the bank,

00:44:29.890 --> 00:44:32.265
or I'm the guy who's threatening
earth with my death ray,

00:44:32.265 --> 00:44:32.860
or something.

00:44:32.860 --> 00:44:34.300
He's the one who's
making the plot happen.

00:44:34.300 --> 00:44:36.174
He's generally the most
interesting character

00:44:36.174 --> 00:44:37.090
in the story.

00:44:37.090 --> 00:44:38.910
And you feel kind
of conflicted when

00:44:38.910 --> 00:44:41.160
you're reading the stories,
or watching a movie,

00:44:41.160 --> 00:44:42.760
or whatever, because
you're like, ah,

00:44:42.760 --> 00:44:45.700
well now this hero is going to
come in and ruin everything.

00:44:45.700 --> 00:44:46.680
Right.

00:44:46.680 --> 00:44:49.660
And in a man versus nature
there's no divided loyalties.

00:44:49.660 --> 00:44:52.220
Nobody roots for nature
in man versus nature.

00:44:52.220 --> 00:44:55.470
It's like, I hope
that guy drowns.

00:44:55.470 --> 00:44:56.640
And so, it's nice.

00:44:56.640 --> 00:45:00.010
And, also, it plays into this
kind of Pollyanna optimism

00:45:00.010 --> 00:45:03.260
that I have in-- this
really is my world view.

00:45:03.260 --> 00:45:05.300
I really think humanity is good.

00:45:05.300 --> 00:45:10.300
Despite how-- despite
what you see in the news.

00:45:10.300 --> 00:45:11.910
I really feel humanity
is good and it

00:45:11.910 --> 00:45:14.720
makes me feel good to see
a bunch of people working

00:45:14.720 --> 00:45:16.720
together to help each other.

00:45:16.720 --> 00:45:19.360
And not a bunch of people
in a war working together

00:45:19.360 --> 00:45:20.693
to kill a bunch of other people.

00:45:20.693 --> 00:45:22.390
But, OK, we're all
going to do this.

00:45:22.390 --> 00:45:25.970
So that's why it's, yeah,
there are bad people

00:45:25.970 --> 00:45:27.470
and they do bad things.

00:45:27.470 --> 00:45:30.110
But the people who do good
things greatly outnumber them.

00:45:30.110 --> 00:45:32.590
And they don't make the news,
because it's just presumed

00:45:32.590 --> 00:45:33.940
as part of human nature.

00:45:33.940 --> 00:45:38.360
And so the quote I always say
is, 19 people made 9/11 happen,

00:45:38.360 --> 00:45:41.070
but thousands of people
rushed in to help.

00:45:41.070 --> 00:45:43.965
So that's my view on
the nature of humanity.

00:45:43.965 --> 00:45:44.715
AUDIENCE: Awesome.

00:45:44.715 --> 00:45:45.590
Thanks very much.

00:45:45.590 --> 00:45:47.965
ANDY WEIR: Sure.

